# No silent frontend failures

## Rule
Every failure surfaces to the user via a toast, dialog, inline message, or router redirect AND is reported to the error tracker (Sentry for React apps, Airbrake for Angular / legacy, Sentry for quote-ai-frontend).

## Why
freightify-web, admin-frontend, and quote-ai-frontend all ship error-tracking integrations. Swallowing errors (`.catch(() => {})` or empty Angular `error` callbacks) produces frustrated users and zero support-side visibility.

## Constraints
- No empty catch blocks. Even "expected" failures (`401` on refresh) must produce a user-visible action (redirect to login, soft-retry with message).
- Error-tracker integration has a `beforeSend` that scrubs tokens, rate data, and PII (see `no-pii-in-logs`).
- Global handlers catch uncaught promise rejections and unhandled errors, reporting them with `correlationId` from the last API call.
- Retry policies are explicit, not implicit; a loop that hides a persistent failure is a bug.

## Examples

### Good
```ts
try { await api.saveRate(rate); toast.success('Saved'); }
catch (e) { toast.error(resolveMessage(e)); Sentry.captureException(e, { tags: { correlationId } }); }
```

### Bad
```ts
api.saveRate(rate).catch(() => {});  // silent loss
```

## Related
- Rules: `structured-logging`, `no-pii-in-logs`.
- Agents: `observability-agent`, `code-review-agent`.
